free_txt: The ANU tandem Van de Graaff accelerator
The measurements were performed  in a 22.9 cm
diam. aluminium scattering chamber  containing two
axially mounted surface barrier detector  assemblies.
One could be locked in position at any  angle, while
the second was rotatable from outside the  chamber
via a simple gear drive. Backlash was < 0.1 and  in
general it was considered possible to set the
detector assembly relative angular position with 0.2
degr. accuracy. The 90 degr. position was occupied by
a  300 Omega*cm ORTEC surface barrier detector fixed
in  the rotatable bracket and the 135 degr. position
by a  3000 Omega*cm ORTEC detector in the fixed
bracket.
The absolute differential cross
section scale contain errors due to inaccuracies in
detector solid angle measurements and uncertainties in
target thickness measurement.

The ANU tandem Van de Graaff accelerator
Proton beam current is 2 mu-A.
Targets were thin self-supporting aluminium films.
Thickness ranged from 10-70 mu-g/cm2, these being
established to 10% accuracy by ThC'-ThC'' alpha
particle energy degradation measurements. The foils
were mounted on a steel strip positioned axially in the
scattering chamber.
